  "runtimeMin": 47,
  "format": "The 25-for-25 countdown reaches No. 9. Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins talk through George Miller's 'Mad Max: Fury Road': the craft, the 2015 Oscar run, and where it ranks among the century's action films.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "No. 9 on the countdown",
      "note": "a 25-for-25 special conversation",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Mad Max: Fury Road",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "George Miller's fourth Mad Max film, conceived in 1978 and released 28 years after 'Beyond Thunderdome.' The hosts call it the best action filmmaking of the century so far: a chase that runs one way and back over a single day, told almost as silent film, with Tom Hardy and Charlize Theron carrying it through faces and glances. Sean rewatched the black-and-chrome edition; both point to the practical stunt work fused with heavy CGI, Junkie XL's score, and the guitar-wielding Doof Warrior. It made about $380 million and won six Oscars below the line while losing Best Picture to 'Spotlight.'"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
